why not just bite the bullet, and buy a dictionary ?<br>
<br>
Hands-down, the best one I ever bought for English speakers who want to learn Japanese is the Collins-Shubun dictionary (hand-size, not the little palm-sized one).  It runs about $5.<br>
<br>
Software can be awfully unreliable, because it's rare enough to get a good dictionary... and doubly rare to get a good programmer, so the conjuction of the two is as rare as pygmy basketball-players.<br>
<br>
Add to that, the whole problem with translation software not giving you decent feedback... like, if you translate &quot;can&quot;, are you sure you're looking at the word for &quot;can-do&quot;, and not the word for &quot;tin-can&quot; ?<br>
<br>
And, when you're finished, run things past a REAL Japanese person.  It's pretty easy to find someone from Japan who'll check your Japanese.<br>
<br>
For example, I teach English in Japan, and I could swing a cat and hit a dozen people who would KILL to practice their English on someone... even if it's language exchange (you check their English, and they check your Japanese). <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#336699>- </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs>Polykarbon BBS</a><font color=#336699> - </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5>Japanese Language Help</a> <font color=#336699> - </font><a href="http://www.polykarbon.com">Polykarbon: Manga & Photoshop</a><font color=#336699> - </font><br><br><table border=0 align=center><tr><td align=center><a href="http://login.ezboard.com/BBSSystem.showUserPaymentScreen" target="_blank">Upgrade your account to ezSupporter...</a></td><td><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/image/spacer.gif" width=15 height=1 border=0></td><td align=center><a href="http://login.ezboard.com/BBSSystem.showUserPaymentScreen" target="_blank">...and never see another ad or pop-up again</a></td></tr></table><CENTER><!-- START BOTTOM AD SCRIPT -->
